claim.claim-text:
8. A method of forming a nonvolatile memory device, comprising:
forming a metal material from about 100 angstroms to about 300 angstroms thick on a chalcogenide material on and in contact with a first electrode by a process selected from the group consisting of physical vapor deposition and chemical vapor deposition;
diffusing metal ions from the metal material into the chalcogenide material to form a fast ion conductor;
forming a seed region of a conductive metal material over the fast ion conductor; and electroless plating another metal material over the fast ion conductor to form a second electrode.

11. A method of forming a nonvolatile memory device, comprising:
contacting a surface of a chalcogenide material with a surface activating agent to form at least one nucleation site, the chalcogenide material on and in contact with a first electrode;
plating a metal material to a thickness of from about 100 angstroms to about 300 angstroms onto the at least one nucleation site;
diffusing metal ions from the metal material into the chalcogenide material to form a fast ion conductor;
plating another metal material over the fast ion conductor to form a second electrode; and
applying a voltage to form a dendrite within the fast ion conductor between the first and second electrodes.

14. A method of forming a phase changeable memory device, comprising:
forming a chalcogenide material on and in contact with a first electrode;
forming a metal material about 100 angstroms to about 300 angstroms thick on the chalcogenide material by a process selected from the group consisting of physical vapor deposition, chemical vapor deposition, and plating;
diffusing metal ions from the metal material into the chalcogenide material to form a fast ion conductor;
plating another material over the fast ion conductor to form a second electrode; and
applying a voltage to form a dendrite within the fast ion conductor material and connecting the first and second electrodes.
